04429nam a22008055i 9780823265602DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232656027 a10.1515/97808232656022doi  a(DE-B1597)555317  a(OCoLC)914229944  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a821/.72231 aGuyer, Sara, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReading with John Clare :bBiopoetics, Sovereignty, Romanticism /cSara Guyer. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (152 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLit Z00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Life of Reading -- t1. The Viability of Poetry -- t2. The Origins and Ends of Poetic Genius -- t3. Can the Poet Speak? -- t4. Inventions of Self - Identity -- t5. The Poetics of Homelessness -- tCoda: The Reading of Life -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReading with John Clare argues that at the heart of contemporary biopolitical thinking is an insistent repression of poetry. By returning to the moment at which biopolitics is said to emerge simultaneously with romanticism, this project renews our understanding of the operations of contemporary politics and its relation to aesthetics across two centuries.Guyer focuses on a single, exemplary case: the poetry and autobiographical writing of the British poet John Clare (1793–1864). Reading Clare in combination with contemporary theories of biopolitics, Guyer reinterprets romanticism’s political legacies, specifically the belief that romanticism is a direct precursor to the violent nationalisms and redemptive environmentalisms of the twentieth and twenty-first centuries.Guyer offers an alternative account of many of romanticism’s foundational concepts, like home, genius, creativity, and organicism. She shows that contemporary critical theories of biopolitics, despite repeatedly dismissing the aesthetic or poetic dimensions of power as a culpable ideology, emerge within the same rhetorical tradition as the romanticism they denounce. The book thus compels a rethinking of the biopolitical critique of poetry and an attendant reconsideration of romanticism and its concepts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAestheticsxPolitical aspects. 0aBiopolitics. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aBiopolitics.  aClose Reading.  aDisplacement.  aGiorgio Agamben.  aHomelessness in Literature.  aJohn Clare.  aLegacies of Romanticism.  aPaul de Man.  aSelf-Identity.  aromanticism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311072903040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823265602zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823265602423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823265602/original  a978-3-11-072903-0  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK